  "prompt": "What's the difference between an appositive and subject compliment?",
  "response": "Let me help you understand the difference:\n\nAppositive:\n- A noun or noun phrase that renames or describes another noun right next to it\n- Provides additional information about the noun\n- Can be removed without changing the sentence's basic meaning\n- Usually set off by commas\n- Example: \"My brother, a talented musician, plays guitar.\"\n\nSubject Complement:\n- A word or phrase that follows a linking verb and describes or renames the subject\n- Provides information about the subject's state or identity\n- Typically either a noun or an adjective\n- Connects directly to the subject through a linking verb like \"is,\" \"seems,\" \"becomes\"\n- Example: \"John is a teacher.\" or \"She seems happy.\"\n\nKey differences:\n1. Position in sentence\n2. Function\n3. Use of commas\n4. Relationship to the rest of the sentence\n\nWould you like me to provide more detailed examples to help clarify the distinction?",
